        [
          "Classification",
          "Intelligent Tutoring System",
          "Next Question Being Correct",
          "Correct (1) vs Incorrect (0)",
          "8300 ASSISTments 2009 sequences, \n67100 ASSISTments 2012 sequences, 2.3M Ednet-KT1, 447.8k Eedi sequences",
          "Not Applicable",
          "ASSIStments, EdNet-KT1, Eedi",
          "[Sequence of Previous Questions,  Answers and Related Concepts, Sequence of Correctedness]",
          "The current KT models often struggle with non-adjacent interactions between question-answer pairs: DKT implicitly models adjacent interactions (hidden state updates of RNN), and few attention models learn both adjacent and non-adjacent interactions. ",
          "MRT-KT introduces a novel form of relationship encoding - unique for each two question-response pairs.\n\nIt also has a multi-relational self-attention mechanism stacked with multi-relational tarrget-dependent attention. \n\nIn addition, the architecture also includes relation-specific temporal kernels.",
          "Inputs (question, concepts, correctedness) are encoded sequentially to be given as input to the model.\n\nRelationships between 2 question-answer pairs are represented by 2-bit (multi-relational target dependent) and 4-bit (multi-relational self-attention). ",
          "DKT, SKT-Forget, SAKT, EKT-A, AKT, HawkesKT, LPKT, SAINT+, MRT-KT",
          "Holdout Method",
          "ASSISTments2009: {AUC: 0.8223 - MRT-KT, Accuracy: 0.7841 - MRT-KT}\n\nASSISTments2012: {AUC: 0.7698 - MRT-KT, Accuracy: 0.7544 - MRT-KT}\n\nEdNet-KT1: {AUC: 0.7753 - MRT-KT, Accuracy: 0.7319 - MRT-KT}\n\nEedi: {AUC: 0.8260 - MRT-KT, Accuracy: 0.7569 - MRT-KT}",
          "Authors propose a model  that includes 3 relationship: \n\n- adjacent past interactions \n- target-dependent interactions between question and past questions, \n- non-adjacent interactions with other questions with distance grater than 1\n\nThe proposed model includes 2 attention layers (one for target interactions and the second for non-adjacent past interactions).\n\nAuthors do a set of experiments to:\n\n1. Assess model performance against other alterrnatives,\n2. Do an ablation study to check the relevance of the different layers introduced in the model.",
          "- Holdout Method\n\n- No probabilistic modelling, which hinders ability to work with open-ended questions."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 7
    }
